            <biogHist>
                <p>Flora or Fionnghal MacLeod was born on North Uist around 1811; her parents were
                    crofters Finlay and Mary MacLellan). By 1841, Flora was living with the Stewart
                    family (John, Marion and their three children) in Claddach Kyles, North Uist,
                    working as an agricultural labourer. Between the 1851 and 1861 censuses, Flora
                    appears to be unmarried and living alone. In March, 1869, Flora was visited by
                    Alexander Carmichael in Baleshare and he collected the song 'Na H-Iolairean'
                    from her; she told him that she heard the song originally from John Stewart. In
                    the 1871 census she is listed as living with members of the Stewart family again
                    and in 1881 as being with John Stewart's two daughters - Mary and Rachel - in
                    Baleshare, North Uist, where she is described as being Mary's Aunt and an
                    annuitant. In 1891, Flora is found living with Rachel Stewart, with other
                    members of the Stewart family living close by (Archibald, son of John, and his
                    family). She died later that year in Baleshare in December 1891, described as a
                    wool spinner. Flora MacLeod is also mentioned in Carmina Gadelica v, 87. </p>
